      "tier3": "Solar panels work through the photovoltaic effect.  This effect describes the creation of voltage or electric current in a material upon exposure to light.  Solar panels are made up of numerous photovoltaic cells, typically composed of silicon.  Silicon is a semiconductor – a material with electrical conductivity between a conductor (like copper) and an insulator (like rubber).  Within each cell, there are layers of silicon with different electrical properties, creating a p-n junction. When sunlight strikes the silicon, photons (light particles) transfer their energy to electrons in the silicon atoms.  This energy excites the electrons, causing them to break free from their atoms.  The p-n junction acts as a one-way valve, directing the flow of these freed electrons, creating a direct current (DC) electricity.  This DC electricity is then collected by conductive materials (metal contacts) on the surface of the cell.  Multiple cells are connected together in series and parallel to create a solar panel, increasing the overall voltage and current output.  An inverter is often used to convert the DC electricity from the solar panel into alternating current (AC) electricity, which is the type of electricity used in most homes and businesses."
